<exercise number="89"><statement><p>Prove the Pythagorean identity <m>1 + \tan^2 \theta = \sec^2 \theta</m>. (Hint: Start with the identity <m>\cos^2 \theta + \sin^2 \theta = 1</m> and divide both sides of the equation by <m>\cos^2 \theta</m>.)</p></statement>
<answer><p>\begin{align*}
            \cos^2 \theta + \sin^2 \theta \amp = 1\\
            \dfrac{\cos^2 \theta}{\cos^2 \theta}+\dfrac{\sin^2 \theta}{\cos^2 \theta}\amp = \dfrac{1}{\cos^2 \theta}\\
            1 + \tan^2 \theta \amp = \sec^2 \theta\\
            \end{align*}</p></answer></exercise>

